Step 1: Create a repository on GitHub

Go to GitHub
 → log in.

Click + → New repository.

Give it a name (e.g., JAVA_OOPS).

Do not initialize with README (we’ll push local folder).

Click Create repository.

✅ You’ll see a page with instructions like this:

git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/JAVA_OOPS.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Step 2: Open your local project folder
cd /path/to/your/folder


Example:

cd ~/Desktop/java_practice/OOPS

Step 3: Initialize Git locally
git init


Creates .git folder → your local Git repository.

Default branch is master (or main depending on Git version).

Step 4: Configure Git identity (first time)
git config --global user.name "Rajesh"
git config --global user.email "your_github_email@example.com"


Required for commits to be linked to your GitHub account.

Step 5: Add files and commit
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"


Adds all files in your folder to the local repository.

Creates the first commit.

Step 6: Connect to GitHub repository (add remote)
git remote add origin https://github.com/skaparth15/JAVA_OOPS.git


origin → nickname for your GitHub repo.

Check connection:

git remote -v


Output:

origin  https://github.com/skaparth15/JAVA_OOPS.git (fetch)
origin  https://github.com/skaparth15/JAVA_OOPS.git (push)

Step 7: Push local branch to GitHub

If local branch is master:

git push -u origin master


If you want to rename local branch to main:

git branch -M main
git push -u origin main


✅ Now your local folder is on GitHub!

Step 8: Verify

Go to your GitHub repository → you should see all files.

Next time, you can just use:

git add .
git commit -m "your message"
git push